SLIDE 1 SCRIPT
“Good afternoon everyone.
Today I’ll be presenting the Streamlit App Enhancement work that I implemented in the Snowflake environment.
This enhancement focuses on automating audit column updates and improving the update process through a user-friendly Streamlit application.
The goal of this work was to reduce manual effort, improve consistency, and simplify the process for users.”

SLIDE 2 SCRIPT
“Before implementing the Streamlit application, users had to manually update column values directly in backend tables.
For example, if someone wanted to change the minimum or maximum display date column values for a particular table, they needed to manually write and execute SQL update statements.
In addition to updating the date values, audit columns such as UPDATE_DATE and UPDATE_USER also needed to be maintained correctly.
This process required technical knowledge and increased the possibility of manual errors.
To simplify this process, a Streamlit-based UI solution was developed where users could update values directly through an interface without needing to manually write SQL queries.”

SLIDE 3 SCRIPT
“An initial version of the Streamlit application called ‘CFG CONTROL APP V2’ was developed by the team to simplify backend table updates through a UI interface.
The application helped reduce manual SQL updates by allowing users to search and update display date values directly through the UI.
During review and testing, a few enhancement opportunities were identified.
For example, audit column updates needed additional automation, and some related backend updates were still being handled manually.
These enhancement areas became the focus of the work I implemented.”

SLIDE 4 SCRIPT
“After reviewing the initial version of the application, I implemented several enhancements to improve automation, accuracy, and user experience.
The main focus areas included automating audit column updates, improving update efficiency, handling Snowflake date edge cases, and enhancing the UI behavior after updates.
These enhancements helped reduce manual intervention and made the application more reliable and user-friendly.”

SLIDE 5 SCRIPT
“One enhancement I implemented was automating the UPDATE_DATE audit column.
Previously, users could manually edit this value, which could lead to inconsistencies.
To improve audit reliability, I removed UPDATE_DATE from editable fields and automatically assigned the latest system timestamp using Snowflake’s current_timestamp() function.
This ensures every update reflects the actual system update time automatically.”

SLIDE 6 SCRIPT
“Another enhancement was automating the UPDATE_USER column.
Instead of users manually entering their name or email, the application now automatically captures the logged-in user information from the Streamlit session.
This improves audit tracking accuracy and reduces manual input errors.”

SLIDE 7 SCRIPT
“To improve efficiency, I implemented logic to identify and update only the rows modified by the user.
Instead of updating the full dataset, the application now processes only changed records.
This reduces unnecessary database operations and improves overall performance.”

SLIDE 8 SCRIPT (Simplified)

“After deployment, we found an issue with one of the date values used in Snowflake, which was 9999-12-31.

Snowflake was able to handle this date correctly, but Pandas could not process this large future date properly.

Because of this, the application was failing during updates for those records.”

SLIDE 9 SCRIPT (Simplified)

“To fix this issue, I added custom logic to handle these special date values before Pandas processed them.

The application now specifically checks for dates like 9999-12-31 and handles them safely.

This fixed the update issue and allowed the application to work correctly with Snowflake date values.”

SLIDE 10 SCRIPT
“One additional UI enhancement involved improving the success message behavior.
Previously, success messages disappeared immediately after the application refreshed.
Using Streamlit session state, I implemented persistent success messaging so users can clearly see update confirmation messages after changes are applied.”

